<HEADLINE>
<P>
DR. JOYCE BROTHERS: BANKROLL, SEX STYLE RELATED? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. JOYCE BROTHERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: Both my husband and I are very generous with money so we're 
surprised that our 17-year-old son is so cautious with his spending. His father 
says that he saves almost everything and has built up quite a bank account. For 
the past year, he's had only one girlfriend and he seems as cautious about 
women as he is about his money. What does this mean? -- V.R. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR V.R.: What you're describing isn't necessarily bad. There does seem to be 
some relationship between fidelity and closeness with money. Psychotherapist 
Rosemarie Schultz, who wrote the book "Sex and Money: Strange Bedfellows," says 
that the way a person handles his bankroll is frequently the way he handles his 
sex life. 
</P>
<P>
Generally, careful spenders are equally cautious about the selection of their 
sex partners, while big spenders may use less discretion and are more likely to 
be unfaithful. 
</P>
<P>
There are just two points, however, that I'd like to make. One, it's generally 
a good idea for young people to date a number of different people before going 
steady, because this is one of the ways in which they learn about themselves. 
And two, it would be a good idea to teach your son to be compassionate and 
generous toward those who have less than he. Empathy and generosity toward the 
less fortunate needs to be taught. Too much thrift can soon become greed. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR DR. BROTHERS: I guess because my wife was left alone a lot as a child, she 
won't leave our baby's side for a moment. But I would like my wife to attend 
social functions with me related to my work. Is it necessary to be with an 
infant every moment? -- G.B. 
</P>
<P>
DEAR G.B.: No. It's healthier to have some separation. Of course, babies need 
round-the-clock care and nurturing, but this doesn't mean that the mother or 
father have no time to themselves. The child's legitimate needs should be 
filled as soon as possible, but there are also times when the baby should be 
left alone to sleep in her own crib or to play by herself. 
</P>
<P>
During the first three or four months, it's a good idea for the baby to sleep 
in the parents' room, but after that it's fine for him to sleep in a room 
nearby. 
</P>
<P>
Little children need to get used to the idea that when mother leaves the room 
or the house she'll return later. If the baby cries, that's fine. This is a 
part of growing up and the fact that mother does return is one of the ways the 
child builds a sense of faith and trust. 
</P>
<P>
Parents need time off for their health, as well as their child's. Encourage 
your wife to go with you. Find a responsible substitute to care for your baby. 
</P>
</TEXT>
