<P>
JUICE CANS WILL BE RECYCLED TOO WITH CAMPBELL, REYNOLDS' PACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
RICHMOND, Va. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Campbell Soup Co. and Reynolds Metals Co. announced today a long-term supply 
agreement under which Reynolds eventually will provide recyclable cans for all 
Campbell's juices. 
</P>
<P>
The agreement includes Campbell's Tomato Juice, V8, Spicy V8 and Juice Bowl 
brands in both 5.5-ounce and 11.5-ounce can sizes. 
</P>
<P>
Reynolds' patented Stay-on-Tab ends also will replace former tape tab ends on 
Campbell's juice cans. 
</P>
<P>
"The same advantages which have made the aluminum beverage can the 
consumer-preferred container in the beer and soft drink markets are also 
applicable to non-carbonated beverages," said Jeremiah Sheehan, vice president 
and general manager of the Reynolds Can Division. 
</P>
<P>
In order to meet Campbell's demands, Reynolds will add new capacity to three 
existing can manufacturing operations. 
</P>
<P>
The Richmond-based company operates 10 aluminum can manufacturing plants and 
two can end-making facilities in the United States. Since 1980, Reynolds said 
it has recycled more aluminum cans than it produces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
